The Nigerian army said on Thursday that its troops of 34 Brigade has captured a cache of arms and ammunition belonging to the Indigenous People of Biafra (IPOB) and its armed affiliate, Eastern Security Network (ESN), after a gun battle at Amaifeke-Akkatta Road in Orlu Local Government Area of Imo State. A statement by Brigadier General Onyema Nwachukwu, Director, Army Public Relations, said the fire arms and ammunition were recovered during troops’ operations to clear separatists’ hideouts in the general area of Amaifeke- Akkatta road. It said that troops uncovered the weapons concealed in a black Toyota Camry, after they successfully surmounted ambushes staged by members of IPOB, who, having been overpowered by the troops, abandoned their vehicle and weapons in the heat of the combat and fled the scene. -Advertisement- “After a thorough search, the troops recovered ten pump action shotguns, seven locally fabricated guns, one locally made revolver pistol, eighty live cartridges, one Baofeng radio and substance suspected to be gun powder. Others include sachet of improvised explosive device (IED) and a Toyota Camry saloon car. “The Nigerian army commends members of the public for their continued support to the military and security agencies, as they protect the citizens from atrocious activities of the outlawed dissident groups, who in defiance of law and good order have annihilated innocent Ndigbo and other Nigerians, in their enforcement of an illegal sit-at-home order, foisted on the good people of the South-East. “The NA urges all to continue to provide timely and credible information in support of ongoing operations to restore peace and security in the South-East and other troubled parts of the country”, the statement read.